narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned about derivatives and integrals. I got better at studying by using the resources on Canvas and going to office hours. So, I learned how to take initiative of my own learning.
I learned how to study for math classes by re-doing problems and having a process for revisiting challenging problems. I also learned about the applications of calculus which was interesting.
I developed my problem-solving skills and solidified my calculus knowledge. This class also helped me acclimate to math at yale and get used to working with problem sets and exams through canvas.
I learned derivatives in depth, and got a thorough introduction to integrals and differential equations.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Ximera was finicky and often difficult to type in long derivatives/antiderivatives. Some concepts were only briefly mentioned, so it'd be nice if the course moved a little slower.
The lectures were too slow for me.

I think the course needs to do more example problems that increase in complexity. I found myself not getting much out of the class sessions themselves, but through resources such as the textbook and online tutorials, along with office hours.
I do not think the PSets reflect the level of questions on exams, they were much harder in general.

The small class sizes are very valuable to students and allow everyone to ask as many questions as they would like. The material was often not taught in preparation for the problem sets and exams which were often quite difficult compared to the material.

The course works well as an introduction to calculus if you've taken some calculus in high school. The Ximera assignments were good for review, but making the way they were graded and the fact that their deadlines were often weeks ahead of the class material meant that they were mostly an annoyance.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: If a student needs to take a calculus course, this is a great option. Otherwise, it felt really repetitive from high school. But in a bad way because I remembered doing similar things but not actually how to do it so it was more confusing the second time.
Yes. It achieved what it promised to.
Yes. If you've taken calculus in high school it's a good course to take. If you haven't I would recommend taking 110 and 111 instead.
I would recommend this course to another student as an introductory math class.

If you're not really required to take it, there are more interesting courses at Yale. If you thought that calculus was interesting in high school and want to learn just a bit more, this course is a solid, albeit uninspiring option.
